== Our Take

Here is our direct perspective on VBAC:

_VBAC should be the default recommendation for most women with one prior low-transverse cesarean._ The evidence overwhelmingly supports this. Success rates of 60-80%, uterine rupture risk under 1%, and substantial benefits for both mother and baby make VBAC the optimal choice for most women in this situation.

_"Once a cesarean, always a cesarean" is outdated and harmful._ This 1916 statement referred to a surgical technique that is no longer used. Continuing to treat all prior cesarean patients as automatic repeat cesareans ignores a century of progress and denies women safer, evidence-based options.

_Access to VBAC is a justice issue._ The fact that only 14% of eligible women attempt VBAC despite 60-80% success rates reveals systemic barriers, not patient choice. Hospital policies driven by liability concerns and financial incentives limit access to evidence-based care.

_Provider choice matters enormously._ VBAC success depends heavily on provider support, patience with labor progress, and avoidance of unnecessary interventions. Choosing a provider with high VBAC rates and evidence-based practices is the single most important action you can take.

_Informed consent must be truly informed._ Many women receive counseling that overstates the risks of VBAC while minimizing the risks of repeat cesarean. Balanced information about both options is essential. The cumulative risks of multiple cesareans must be part of the discussion, especially for women planning more children.

_Uterine rupture is serious but rare._ While the consequences can be severe, the risk is comparable to many other accepted pregnancy risks. The key is appropriate screening (excluding high-risk uterine incisions), continuous monitoring during labor, and capability for rapid cesarean if needed.

_Spontaneous labor is crucial._ Whenever possible, avoid induction. The 79% success rate with spontaneous labor versus 66% with induction is a significant difference. Routine early induction of TOLAC patients sets them up for failure.

_Time limits and arbitrary restrictions harm VBAC success._ Many repeat cesareans performed during TOLAC are due to institutional policies, not medical necessity. Women deserve adequate time for labor to progress, freedom to eat and drink, and ability to move and use comfort measures.

_VBAC heals._ For many women, particularly those with traumatic previous cesarean experiences, achieving VBAC is profoundly empowering. Even for those who end up with repeat cesarean, the experience of trying and being supported through the process can provide closure.

_Repeat cesarean is sometimes the right choice._ For women with classical incisions, previous uterine rupture, or multiple prior cesareans, planned repeat cesarean may be genuinely safer. For others, the certainty and control of scheduled surgery may outweigh the benefits of VBAC attempt. What matters is that the decision is informed and autonomous.

_We need systemic change._ VBAC access should not depend on where you live or which provider you happen to choose. Hospitals and providers should be held accountable for VBAC rates, transparent about their practices, and required to offer evidence-based TOLAC to eligible women.

_Your body, your choice, your birth._ Whether you attempt VBAC or choose planned cesarean, you deserve accurate information, respectful care, and support for your decision. No one else lives with the consequences of this choice. Trust yourself.

